Hi, I am a retired teacher (systems, electronics and robotics). I use a CEL-Robox 3-D printer. It was my main introduction to 3-D printing. Here is the manufacturer's website. http://www.cel-robox.com/

The Robox comes assembled and calibrated. It has auto spool/plastic detection, two nozzles for same plastic (or now two different materials), one coarse and one fine. It also has a self leveling bed, plus is (usually) very reliable, and gives excellent, reproducible results . Running on Ubuntu Mate 16.04 LTS at the moment and very pleased with it. Its biggest draw back is that it uses many factory designed parts that are impossible to replace with stock parts. Consequently if anything goes wrong (and it has lately, eg 24V power connection to print head is ultra unreliable) it can be very expensive to replace. Recommended for people who are cashed up, and not many technical skills.

However I am having a lot more fun modding up my Anet-A8 and knowing that I can replace anything that breaks or wears out at a modest cost. This printer is very educational too and produces excellent prints, and is a very cost effective solution. Highly recommended.

Update: I have since modified my A8 to an AM8 using Pheneeny's build to make a from from 2020 Aluminium extrusion and 3-D printed parts. This has worked well and is highly recommended as a great project that improves the printer considerably.

Our brand (3Dreams) focuses on providing particular 3D services such as: modeling, production of 3D models and prototypes for consumers and small businesses, Selling 3D desktop printers & 3D printing accessories.
3D printing is not a new technology, but there is a common claim that in the next decade it will truly revolutionize the industrial sector and product manufacturing process.
Moreover, from this common claim is that 3D printing technology eventually will be adopted by every home in Israel. 3Dreams sets a goal to become the leading brand of 3D products line and service in Israel. Furthermore, we aim to provide an interactive, well-designed web interface in order to make this technology more accessible and approachable for the Israeli market.

PaLEoS (Projects and Learning Experiences of Science) è una società che opera nel campo dell'educazione scientifica e tecnologica e si occupa di promozione culturale e formazione per il grande pubblico, attraverso un approccio che arricchisce il paradigma della STEM education con l'educazione ambientale e le esperienze attinenti alle scienze naturali.

PaLEoS ha investito e scommesso sulle enormi potenzialità della stampa 3D e delle tecnologie interattive di prototipazione rapida (Arduino, microcomputer programmabile) come strumenti innovativi per la didattica e la divulgazione presso il grande pubblico.

PaLEoS organizza e promuove corsi di formazione e laboratori per l'apprendimento della scienza e della tecnologia presso le proprie strutture, destinati a specifiche categorie (insegnanti, formatori, educatori, etc.) o per il grande pubblico e fornisce consulenza su temi come ricerca e divulgazione mediata dalle nuove tecnologie.

Grazie alla personal fabrication, progetta e sviluppa sussidi e prodotti per l'apprendimento a basso costo e personalizzati destinati a scuole, centri di apprendimento, musei e grande pubblico.

(like that: http://toonfreak.deviantart.com/art/FLCL-Motivational-Poster-284119554 )

3D printing is cool but I personally don't think it will turn the world upside down. It is expectable though that in the not too distant future very small (e.g. smartphone sized) additive manufacturing devices that are capable of accurately and parallely putting massive amounts of single carbon atoms together will pop up. Such Atomically precise small scale factroies or personal fabricators undoubtably will lead to swift and radical change of unprecedented magnitude.

If you're interested here's a link to my wiki about this topic
where I started to gather some rudimentary bits of relevant information:

bio:
Hi,

I am Baschz, an artist, designer and maker from the Netherlands with a profound love for hand made things with a mass production look and feel to them.

3D printing has given me the possibility to by hand and in house create small run (art) projects that look like they were pooped out by the thousands in a factory far far away. You can find some of these products in my webshop Lamball Bakra, where I sell 3D-printed objects, enamel pins, screen prints, T-shirts and other cool stuff. I also use 3D-printing in other work and to fix or upgrade things around the house, my studio, or on my printers.
